33// compilation to native code.

36// allocation and constant-time deallocation of the entire syntax
37// tree.

142class AstNode: public ZoneObject {
143 public:
144#define DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM(type) k##type,
145 enum NodeType : uint8_t {
146 AST_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM) /* , */
147 FAILURE_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM)
148 };
149#undef DECLARE_TYPE_ENUM
150
151 NodeType node_type() const { return NodeTypeField::decode(bit_field_); }
152 int position() const { return position_; }
153
154#ifdef DEBUG
155 void Print(Isolate* isolate);
156#endif // DEBUG
157
158 // Type testing & conversion functions overridden by concrete subclasses.
159#define DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS(type) \
160 V8_INLINE bool Is##type() const; \
161 V8_INLINE type* As##type(); \
162 V8_INLINE const type* As##type() const;
163 AST_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS)
164 FAILURE_NODE_LIST(DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS)
165#undef DECLARE_NODE_FUNCTIONS
166
167 IterationStatement* AsIterationStatement();
168 MaterializedLiteral* AsMaterializedLiteral();
169
170 private:
171 int position_;
172 using NodeTypeField = base::BitField<NodeType, 0, 6>;
173
174 protected:
175 uint32_t bit_field_;
176
177 template <class T, int size>
178 using NextBitField = NodeTypeField::Next<T, size>;
179
180 AstNode(int position, NodeType type)
181 : position_(position), bit_field_(NodeTypeField::encode(type)) {}
182};

191class Expression : public AstNode {
192 public:
193 enum Context {
194 // Not assigned a context yet, or else will not be visited during
195 // code generation.
196 kUninitialized,

198 kEffect,
199 // Evaluated for its value (and side effects).
200 kValue,
201 // Evaluated for control flow (and side effects).
202 kTest
203 };
204
205 // True iff the expression is a valid reference expression.
206 bool IsValidReferenceExpression() const;
207
208 // True iff the expression is a private name.
209 bool IsPrivateName() const;
210
211 // Helpers for ToBoolean conversion.
212 bool ToBooleanIsTrue() const;
213 bool ToBooleanIsFalse() const;
214
215 // Symbols that cannot be parsed as array indices are considered property
216 // names. We do not treat symbols that can be array indexes as property
217 // names because [] for string objects is handled only by keyed ICs.
218 bool IsPropertyName() const;
219
220 // True iff the expression is a class or function expression without
221 // a syntactic name.
222 bool IsAnonymousFunctionDefinition() const;
223
224 // True iff the expression is a concise method definition.
225 bool IsConciseMethodDefinition() const;
226
227 // True iff the expression is an accessor function definition.
228 bool IsAccessorFunctionDefinition() const;
229
230 // True iff the expression is a literal represented as a smi.
231 bool IsSmiLiteral() const;
232
233 // True iff the expression is a literal represented as a number.
234 V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE bool IsNumberLiteral() const;
235
236 // True iff the expression is a string literal.
237 bool IsStringLiteral() const;
238
239 // True iff the expression is the null literal.
240 bool IsNullLiteral() const;
241
242 bool IsBooleanLiteral() const;
243
244 // True iff the expression is the hole literal.
245 bool IsTheHoleLiteral() const;
246
247 // True if we can prove that the expression is the undefined literal. Note
248 // that this also checks for loads of the global "undefined" variable.
249 bool IsUndefinedLiteral() const;
250
251 // True if either null literal or undefined literal.
252 inline bool IsNullOrUndefinedLiteral() const {
253 return IsNullLiteral() || IsUndefinedLiteral();
254 }
255
256 // True if a literal and not null or undefined.
257 bool IsLiteralButNotNullOrUndefined() const;
258
259 bool IsCompileTimeValue();
260
261 bool IsPattern() {
262 static_assert(kObjectLiteral + 1 == kArrayLiteral);
263 return base::IsInRange(node_type(), kObjectLiteral, kArrayLiteral);

265

297// V8's notion of BreakableStatement does not correspond to the notion of
298// BreakableStatement in ECMAScript. In V8, the idea is that a
299// BreakableStatement is a statement that can be the target of a break
300// statement.
301//
302// Since we don't want to track a list of labels for all kinds of statements, we
303// only declare switchs, loops, and blocks as BreakableStatements. This means
304// that we implement breaks targeting other statement forms as breaks targeting
305// a substatement thereof. For instance, in "foo: if (b) { f(); break foo; }" we
306// pretend that foo is the label of the inner block. That's okay because one
307// can't observe the difference.
308// TODO(verwaest): Reconsider this optimization now that the tracking of labels
309// is done at runtime.
310class BreakableStatement : public Statement {
311 protected:
312 BreakableStatement(int position, NodeType type) : Statement(position, type) {}
313};
314
315class Block final : public BreakableStatement {
316 public:
317 ZonePtrList<Statement>* statements() { return &statements_; }
318 bool ignore_completion_value() const {
319 return IgnoreCompletionField::decode(bit_field_);
320 }
321 bool is_breakable() const { return IsBreakableField::decode(bit_field_); }
322
323 Scope* scope() const { return scope_; }
324 void set_scope(Scope* scope) { scope_ = scope; }
325
326 void InitializeStatements(const ScopedPtrList<Statement>& statements,
327 Zone* zone) {
328 DCHECK_EQ(0, statements_.length());
329 statements_ = ZonePtrList<Statement>(statements.ToConstVector(), zone);
330 }
331
332 private:
333 friend class AstNodeFactory;
334 friend Zone;
335
336 ZonePtrList<Statement> statements_;
337 Scope* scope_;
338
339 using IgnoreCompletionField = BreakableStatement::NextBitField<bool, 1>;
340 using IsBreakableField = IgnoreCompletionField::Next<bool, 1>;
341
342 protected:
343 Block(Zone* zone, int capacity, bool ignore_completion_value,
344 bool is_breakable)
345 : BreakableStatement(kNoSourcePosition, kBlock),
346 statements_(capacity, zone),
347 scope_(nullptr) {
348 bit_field_ |= IgnoreCompletionField::encode(ignore_completion_value) |
349 IsBreakableField::encode(is_breakable);
350 }
351
352 Block(bool ignore_completion_value, bool is_breakable)
353 : Block(nullptr, 0, ignore_completion_value, is_breakable) {}
354};

774class TryCatchStatement final : public TryStatement {
775 public:
776 Scope* scope() { return scope_; }
777 Block* catch_block() const { return catch_block_; }
778 void set_catch_block(Block* b) { catch_block_ = b; }
779
780 // Prediction of whether exceptions thrown into the handler for this try block
781 // will be caught.
782 //
783 // BytecodeGenerator tracks the state of catch prediction, which can change
784 // with each TryCatchStatement encountered. The tracked catch prediction is
785 // later compiled into the code's handler table. The runtime uses this
786 // information to implement a feature that notifies the debugger when an
787 // uncaught exception is thrown, _before_ the exception propagates to the top.
788 //
789 // If this try/catch statement is meant to rethrow (HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT),
790 // the catch prediction value is set to the same value as the surrounding
791 // catch prediction.
792 //
793 // Since it's generally undecidable whether an exception will be caught, our
794 // prediction is only an approximation.
795 // ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
796 inline HandlerTable::CatchPrediction GetCatchPrediction(
797 HandlerTable::CatchPrediction outer_catch_prediction) const {
798 if (catch_prediction_ == HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT) {
799 return outer_catch_prediction;
800 }
801 return catch_prediction_;
802 }
803
804 // Indicates whether or not code should be generated to clear the pending
805 // exception. The exception is cleared for cases where the exception
806 // is not guaranteed to be rethrown, indicated by the value
807 // HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT. If both the current and surrounding catch handler's
808 // are predicted uncaught, the exception is not cleared.
809 //
810 // If this handler is not going to simply rethrow the exception, this method
811 // indicates that the isolate's exception message should be cleared
812 // before executing the catch_block.
813 // In the normal use case, this flag is always on because the message object
814 // is not needed anymore when entering the catch block and should not be
815 // kept alive.
816 // The use case where the flag is off is when the catch block is guaranteed
817 // to rethrow the caught exception (using %ReThrow), which reuses the
818 // pending message instead of generating a new one.
819 // (When the catch block doesn't rethrow but is guaranteed to perform an
820 // ordinary throw, not clearing the old message is safe but not very
821 // useful.)
822 //
823 // For scripts in repl mode there is exactly one catch block with
824 // UNCAUGHT_ASYNC_AWAIT prediction. This catch block needs to preserve
825 // the exception so it can be re-used later by the inspector.
826 inline bool ShouldClearException(
827 HandlerTable::CatchPrediction outer_catch_prediction) const {
828 if (catch_prediction_ == HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT_ASYNC_AWAIT) {
829 DCHECK_EQ(outer_catch_prediction, HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT);
830 return false;
831 }
832
833 return catch_prediction_ != HandlerTable::UNCAUGHT ||

1106// Base class for build literal boilerplate, providing common code for handling
1107// nested subliterals.
1108class LiteralBoilerplateBuilder {
1109 public:
1110 enum DepthKind { kUninitialized, kShallow, kNotShallow };
1111
1112 static constexpr int kDepthKindBits = 2;
1113 static_assert((1 << kDepthKindBits) > kNotShallow);
1114
1115 bool is_initialized() const {
1116 return kUninitialized != DepthField::decode(bit_field_);
1117 }
1118 DepthKind depth() const {
1119 DCHECK(is_initialized());
1120 return DepthField::decode(bit_field_);
1121 }
1122
1123 // If the expression is a literal, return the literal value;
1124 // if the expression is a materialized literal and is_simple
1125 // then return an Array or Object Boilerplate Description
1126 // Otherwise, return undefined literal as the placeholder
1127 // in the object literal boilerplate.
1128 template <typename IsolateT>
1129 static Handle<Object> GetBoilerplateValue(Expression* expression,
1130 IsolateT* isolate);
1131
1132 bool is_shallow() const { return depth() == kShallow; }
1133 bool needs_initial_allocation_site() const {
1134 return NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::decode(bit_field_);
1135 }
1136
1137 int ComputeFlags(bool disable_mementos = false) const {
1138 int flags = AggregateLiteral::kNoFlags;
1139 if (is_shallow()) flags |= AggregateLiteral::kIsShallow;
1140 if (disable_mementos) flags |= AggregateLiteral::kDisableMementos;
1141 if (needs_initial_allocation_site())
1142 flags |= AggregateLiteral::kNeedsInitialAllocationSite;
1143 return flags;
1144 }
1145
1146 // An AggregateLiteral is simple if the values consist of only
1147 // constants and simple object and array literals.
1148 bool is_simple() const { return IsSimpleField::decode(bit_field_); }
1149
1150 ElementsKind boilerplate_descriptor_kind() const {
1151 return BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::decode(bit_field_);
1152 }
1153
1154 private:
1155 // we actually only care three conditions for depth
1156 // - depth == kUninitialized, DCHECK(!is_initialized())
1157 // - depth == kShallow, which means depth = 1
1158 // - depth == kNotShallow, which means depth > 1
1159 using DepthField = base::BitField<DepthKind, 0, kDepthKindBits>;
1160 using NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField = DepthField::Next<bool, 1>;
1161 using IsSimpleField = NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::Next<bool, 1>;
1162 using BoilerplateDescriptorKindField =
1163 IsSimpleField::Next<ElementsKind, kFastElementsKindBits>;
1164
1165 protected:
1166 uint32_t bit_field_;
1167
1168 LiteralBoilerplateBuilder() {
1169 bit_field_ =
1170 DepthField::encode(kUninitialized) |
1171 NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::encode(false) |
1172 IsSimpleField::encode(false) |
1173 BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::encode(FIRST_FAST_ELEMENTS_KIND);
1174 }
1175
1176 void set_is_simple(bool is_simple) {
1177 bit_field_ = IsSimpleField::update(bit_field_, is_simple);
1178 }
1179
1180 void set_boilerplate_descriptor_kind(ElementsKind kind) {
1181 DCHECK(IsFastElementsKind(kind));
1182 bit_field_ = BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::update(bit_field_, kind);
1183 }
1184
1185 void set_depth(DepthKind depth) {
1186 DCHECK(!is_initialized());
1187 bit_field_ = DepthField::update(bit_field_, depth);
1188 }
1189
1190 void set_needs_initial_allocation_site(bool required) {
1191 bit_field_ = NeedsInitialAllocationSiteField::update(bit_field_, required);
1192 }
1193
1194 // Populate the depth field and any flags the literal builder has
1195 static void InitDepthAndFlags(MaterializedLiteral* expr);
1196
1197 // Populate the constant properties/elements fixed array.
1198 template <typename IsolateT>
1199 void BuildConstants(IsolateT* isolate, MaterializedLiteral* expr);
1200
1201 template <class T, int size>
1202 using NextBitField = BoilerplateDescriptorKindField::Next<T, size>;
1203};

1550 while (*n != nullptr && (*n)->is_removed_from_unresolved()) {

1554 }

1615// Assignments to a property will use one of several types of property access.
1616// Otherwise, the assignment is to a non-property (a global, a local slot, a
1617// parameter slot, or a destructuring pattern).
1618enum AssignType {
1619 NON_PROPERTY, // destructuring
1620 NAMED_PROPERTY, // obj.key
1621 KEYED_PROPERTY, // obj[key] and obj.#key when #key is a private field
1622 NAMED_SUPER_PROPERTY, // super.key
1623 KEYED_SUPER_PROPERTY, // super[key]
1624 PRIVATE_METHOD, // obj.#key: #key is a private method
1625 PRIVATE_GETTER_ONLY, // obj.#key: #key only has a getter defined
1626 PRIVATE_SETTER_ONLY, // obj.#key: #key only has a setter defined
1627 PRIVATE_GETTER_AND_SETTER, // obj.#key: #key has both accessors defined
1628 PRIVATE_DEBUG_DYNAMIC, // obj.#key: #key is private that requries dynamic
1629 // lookup in debug-evaluate.
1630};

1632class Property final : public Expression {
1633 public:
1634 bool is_optional_chain_link() const {
1635 return IsOptionalChainLinkField::decode(bit_field_);
1636 }
1637
1638 bool IsValidReferenceExpression() const { return true; }
1639
1640 Expression* obj() const { return obj_; }
1641 Expression* key() const { return key_; }
1642
1643 bool IsSuperAccess() { return obj()->IsSuperPropertyReference(); }
1644 bool IsPrivateReference() const { return key()->IsPrivateName(); }
1645
1646 // Returns the properties assign type.
1647 static AssignType GetAssignType(Property* property) {
1648 if (property == nullptr) return NON_PROPERTY;
1649 if (property->IsPrivateReference()) {
1650 DCHECK(!property->IsSuperAccess());
1651 VariableProxy* proxy = property->key()->AsVariableProxy();
1652 DCHECK_NOT_NULL(proxy);
1653 Variable* var = proxy->var();
1654
1655 switch (var->mode()) {
1656 case VariableMode::kPrivateMethod:
1657 return PRIVATE_METHOD;
1658 case VariableMode::kConst:
1659 return KEYED_PROPERTY; // Use KEYED_PROPERTY for private fields.
1660 case VariableMode::kPrivateGetterOnly:
1661 return PRIVATE_GETTER_ONLY;
1662 case VariableMode::kPrivateSetterOnly:
1663 return PRIVATE_SETTER_ONLY;
1664 case VariableMode::kPrivateGetterAndSetter:
1665 return PRIVATE_GETTER_AND_SETTER;
1666 case VariableMode::kDynamic:
1667 // From debug-evaluate.
1668 return PRIVATE_DEBUG_DYNAMIC;
1669 default:
1670 UNREACHABLE();
1671 }
1672 }
1673 bool super_access = property->IsSuperAccess();
1674 return (property->key()->IsPropertyName())
1675 ? (super_access ? NAMED_SUPER_PROPERTY : NAMED_PROPERTY)
1676 : (super_access ? KEYED_SUPER_PROPERTY : KEYED_PROPERTY);
1677 }
1678
1679 private:
1680 friend class AstNodeFactory;
1681 friend Zone;
1682

1684 : Expression(pos, kProperty), obj_(obj), key_(key) {
1685 bit_field_ |= IsOptionalChainLinkField::encode(optional_chain);
1686 }

2823// ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
2824// Basic visitor
2825// Sub-class should parametrize AstVisitor with itself, e.g.:
2826// class SpecificVisitor : public AstVisitor<SpecificVisitor> { ... }
2827
2828template <class Subclass>
2829class AstVisitor {
2830 public:
2831 void Visit(AstNode* node) { impl()->Visit(node); }
2832
2833 void VisitDeclarations(Declaration::List* declarations) {
2834 for (Declaration* decl : *declarations) Visit(decl);
2835 }
2836
2837 void VisitStatements(const ZonePtrList<Statement>* statements) {
2838 for (int i = 0; i < statements->length(); i++) {
2839 Statement* stmt = statements->at(i);
2840 Visit(stmt);
2841 }
2842 }
2843
2844 void VisitExpressions(const ZonePtrList<Expression>* expressions) {
2845 for (int i = 0; i < expressions->length(); i++) {
2846 // The variable statement visiting code may pass null expressions
2847 // to this code. Maybe this should be handled by introducing an
2848 // undefined expression or literal? Revisit this code if this
2849 // changes.
2850 Expression* expression = expressions->at(i);
2851 if (expression != nullptr) Visit(expression);
2852 }
2853 }
2854
2855 protected:
2856 Subclass* impl() { return static_cast<Subclass*>(this); }
2857};

2859#define GENERATE_VISIT_CASE(NodeType) \
2860 case AstNode::k##NodeType: \
2861 return this->impl()->Visit##NodeType(static_cast<NodeType*>(node));
2862
2863#define GENERATE_FAILURE_CASE(NodeType) \
2864 case AstNode::k##NodeType: \
2865 UNREACHABLE();
2866
2867#define GENERATE_AST_VISITOR_SWITCH() \
2868 switch (node->node_type()) { \
2869 AST_NODE_LIST(GENERATE_VISIT_CASE) \
2870 FAILURE_NODE_LIST(GENERATE_FAILURE_CASE) \
2871 }
2872
2873#define DEFINE_AST_VISITOR_SUBCLASS_MEMBERS() \
2874 public: \
2875 void VisitNoStackOverflowCheck(AstNode* node) { \
2876 GENERATE_AST_VISITOR_SWITCH() \
2877 } \
2878 \
2879 void Visit(AstNode* node) { \
2880 if (CheckStackOverflow()) return; \
2881 VisitNoStackOverflowCheck(node); \
2882 } \
2883 \
2884 void SetStackOverflow() { stack_overflow_ = true; } \
2885 void ClearStackOverflow() { stack_overflow_ = false; } \
2886 bool HasStackOverflow() const { return stack_overflow_; } \
2887 \
2888 bool CheckStackOverflow() { \
2889 if (stack_overflow_) return true; \
2890 if (GetCurrentStackPosition() < stack_limit_) { \
2891 stack_overflow_ = true; \
2892 return true; \
2893 } \
2894 return false; \
2895 } \
2896 \
2897 protected: \
2898 uintptr_t stack_limit() const { return stack_limit_; } \
2899 \
2900 private: \
2901 void InitializeAstVisitor(Isolate* isolate) { \
2902 stack_limit_ = isolate->stack_guard()->real_climit(); \
2903 stack_overflow_ = false; \
2904 } \
2905 \
2906 void InitializeAstVisitor(uintptr_t stack_limit) { \
2907 stack_limit_ = stack_limit; \
2908 stack_overflow_ = false; \
2909 } \

3302 Assignment* NewAssignment(Token::Value op,
3303 Expression* target,
3304 Expression* value,
3305 int pos) {
3306 DCHECK(Token::IsAssignmentOp(op));
3307 DCHECK_NOT_NULL(target);
3308 DCHECK_NOT_NULL(value);
3309
3310 if (op != Token::kInit && target->IsVariableProxy()) {
3311 target->AsVariableProxy()->set_is_assigned();
3312 }
3313
3314 if (op == Token::kAssign || op == Token::kInit) {
3315 return zone_->New<Assignment>(AstNode::kAssignment, op, target, value,
3316 pos);
3317 } else {
3318 return zone_->New<CompoundAssignment>(
3319 op, target, value, pos,
3320 NewBinaryOperation(Token::BinaryOpForAssignment(op), target, value,
3321 pos + 1));
3322 }
3323 }
